{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"alias":"fixed-jockeyish-swan","description":"# S7 — Documentation, ADR, and regenerated references for MCP auth\n\n## Why\nThe capability must be usable and auditable by a third-party operator, and the design decisions\nmust be recorded for maintainers and the rigorous security review. This story writes the operator\nguide, the architectural decision record, and regenerates the derived reference artifacts so the\ndocs match the shipped surface.\n\n## What\n- New `docs/mcp-auth.md`: the operator guide — how to enable the HTTP transport + auth; each of the\n  five verifier modes with config examples; the security model (resource-server-only, mandatory\n  audience validation, fail-closed, DNS-rebinding, no token passthrough); behind-a-proxy /\n  TLS-at-edge deployment guidance; and the bearer-token security checklist a reviewer uses.\n- A new ADR under `docs/adr/` recording: the resource-server-only decision (no Authorization\n  Server / no DCR), building our own verifiers on the official SDK seam (vs adopting standalone\n  `fastmcp`), the five shipped verifier modes, the security posture, and the explicitly deferred\n  items (AS/DCR, per-tool scope authz, AWS deployment).\n- Regenerate `docs/mcp-reference.md` and `docs/env-vars.md` (their generators) and finalize\n  `server.json` so all new `REBAR_MCP_*` keys are documented; confirm the CI drift gates pass.\n\n## Approach & rationale\nDocumentation-and-ADR story deliberately sequenced last so it documents the *actually shipped*\nsurface (S1–S6) rather than a projected one; regeneration (not hand-editing) keeps the derived\ndocs authoritative and drift-gated. This is a docs/mechanical leaf — no runtime behavior.\n\n## Scope\nDocs, the ADR, and regenerated reference/manifest artifacts only. No code behavior. Subset of the\nepic. Depends on S1–S6 (documents them).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `docs/mcp-auth.md` exists and covers: enabling HTTP+auth; all five verifier modes with a\n      config example each; the security model; and behind-a-proxy/TLS deployment guidance\n      (observable oracle: the file exists and a docs-completeness check / link check passes).\n- [ ] An ADR file exists under `docs/adr/` recording the resource-server-only + build-own decision,\n      the five modes, and the deferred items.\n- [ ] `docs/mcp-reference.md` and `docs/env-vars.md` are regenerated and the CI drift gates for\n      them and for `server.json` pass (observable oracle: `make test` / the manifest-check job is\n      green with the new keys present).\n- [ ] `make lint && make test` pass (this is a docs/mechanical leaf; no typecheck-relevant code).\n\n## Compatibility\nDocs only; no runtime or dependency change beyond what S1–S6 introduced.","id":"4c7f-4fd3-11ce-474c","parent_id":"3393-83ca-5501-4e6e","priority":2,"tags":["mcp","auth","docs"],"ticket_type":"story","title":"S7 — Documentation, ADR, and regenerated references for MCP auth"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"CREATE","timestamp":1784060333983447001,"uuid":"a07d5033-9224-4786-b098-04995b2e304a"}